docs.abstract: At an experimental store on the ground floor of a new Amazon office building in Seattle, shoppers will be able to pluck what they want off the shelves and leave without waiting to pay.
docs.snippet: At an experimental store on the ground floor of a new Amazon office building in Seattle, shoppers will be able to pluck what they want off the shelves and leave without waiting to pay.
docs.lead_paragraph: SEATTLE — There is almost no aspect of retail that Amazon has not upended with online shopping. Now, the company is trying to computerize the experience of buying sandwiches and soda from the corner convenience store.

headline.main: Amazon Moves to Cut Checkout Line, Promoting a Grab-and-Go Experience
headline.print_headline: Amazon Cuts Checkout Line at New Grab-and-Go Store

docs.abstract: The shape-shifting character actor reflects on his roles in “Office Space” and the “prescient” Amazon series “The Man in the High Castle.”
docs.snippet: The shape-shifting character actor reflects on his roles in “Office Space” and the “prescient” Amazon series “The Man in the High Castle.”
docs.lead_paragraph: You’ve seen Stephen Root far more than you might think. He’s the shape-shifting character actor you know you recognize, but can’t place. Of course, there’s his unforgettable creation from the cult classic “Office Space”: Milton, the stapler-obsessed arsonist hidden under extremely thick glasses, stilted speech and a pocket protector. But Mr. Root has mined a number of idiosyncratic veins over the past several decades, with memorable parts in films like “No Country for Old Men,” TV shows as disparate as “NewsRadio, “Louie” and “Boardwalk Empire,” and voice work in animated ones like “King of the Hill” and “Adventure Time.”

headline.main: Stephen Root Is Just the Man for a Cubicle or a Castle
headline.print_headline: Stephen Root, at Home in a Cubicle or a Castle

docs.abstract: The wide array of available video-streaming devices can be overwhelming, but a bit of research will help you figure out what features you really need.

docs.lead_paragraph: Q. There seems to be quite a range of prices on streaming video set-top boxes and sticks. What more do you really get with the more expensive ones priced at $150 or more, compared with the plug-in sticks that cost $30 to $40?

headline.main: The Quest for Your Dream Streamer
